.TH LIST 3 "January 2025" "list.h" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
list.h \- Doubly\-linked list operations
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include <list.h>

List Construction and Management:
.br
.B void list_clear(list_t *list);

Element Access:
.br
.B node_t *list_back(list_t *list);
.br
.B node_t *list_front(list_t *list);

Element Insertion:
.br
.B void list_insert(list_t *list, void *element, size_t n, type_t type, int position);
.br
.B void list_push_back(list_t *list, void *element, size_t n, type_t type);
.br
.B void list_push_front(list_t *list, void *element, size_t n, type_t type);

Element Removal:
.br
.B node_t *list_erase(list_t *list, int position);
.br
.B node_t *list_pop_back(list_t *list);
.br
.B node_t *list_pop_front(list_t *list);

Query and Inspection:
.br
.B bool list_empty(list_t *list);
.br
.B size_t list_size(list_t *list);

Iteration and Navigation:
.br
.B node_t *list_begin(list_t *list);
.br
.B node_t *list_end(list_t *list);

List Modification:
.br
.B void list_merge(list_t *one, list_t *two);
.br
.B void list_reverse(list_t *list);
.br
.B void list_sort(list_t *list);
.br
.B void list_unique(list_t *list);
.SH DESCRIPTION
List Construction and Management:
.RS
.IP \[bu]
.B list_clear:
Removes all elements from the list, freeing all associated memory.
.RE

Element Access:
.RS
.IP \[bu]
.B list_back:
Returns the last node in the list. Returns NULL if the list is empty.
.IP \[bu]
.B list_front:
Returns the first node in the list. Returns NULL if the list is empty.
.RE

Element Insertion:
.RS
.IP \[bu]
.B list_insert:
Inserts an element at the specified position. If position is out of bounds, the function does nothing.
.IP \[bu]
.B list_push_back:
Adds an element to the end of the list. 
.IP \[bu]
.B list_push_front:
Adds an element to the beginning of the list.
.RE

Element Removal:
.RS
.IP \[bu]
.B list_erase:
Removes and returns the node at the specified position. Returns NULL if position is invalid.
.IP \[bu]
.B list_pop_back:
Removes and returns the last node. Returns NULL if the list is empty.
.IP \[bu]
.B list_pop_front:
Removes and returns the first node. Returns NULL if the list is empty.
.RE

Query and Inspection:
.RS
.IP \[bu]
.B list_empty:
Returns true if the list has no elements, false otherwise.
.IP \[bu]
.B list_size:
Returns the number of elements in the list.
.RE

Iteration and Navigation:
.RS
.IP \[bu]
.B list_begin:
Returns the first node for iteration. Use with caution as it returns NULL if the list is empty.
.IP \[bu]
.B list_end:
Returns the last node for iteration in a doubly-linked list. Returns NULL if the list is empty.
.RE

List Modification:
.RS
.IP \[bu]
.B list_merge:
Merges another list into this one, leaving the second list empty. 
.IP \[bu]
.B list_reverse:
Reverses the order of elements in the list.
.IP \[bu]
.B list_sort:
Sorts the elements in the list based on memory comparison. Note: Assumes all elements are of the same size and type.
.IP \[bu]
.B list_unique:
Removes all but the first of consecutive equal elements based on memory comparison.

Additionally, 
.B list_register_user_type
can be used to register new user-defined types:

.B void list_register_user_type(type_t *type, size_t size);

.RE

Usage:
.RS
.IP \[bu]
The list is designed to handle any data type through void pointers. Users must manage type safety.
.IP \[bu]
When freeing nodes returned by pop or erase operations, use the helper function 
.B free_node(node_t *node).
.IP \[bu]
To iterate over the list, use 
.B list_begin()
and continue until you reach 
.B list_end()
or NULL.
.RE

Possible Error Conditions:
.RS
.IP \[bu]
Memory allocation failures could occur in node creation. Functions return NULL or do nothing in such cases.
.IP \[bu]
Invalid indices in 
.B list_insert
or 
.B list_erase
will result in no operation performed.
.IP \[bu]
Attempting to access or remove from an empty list might return NULL or lead to unexpected behavior.
.RE
.SH EXAMPLE
Here's an example demonstrating basic usage of the list functions, including registering a user-defined type:

.nf
#include <stdio.h>
#include <list.h>

typedef struct {
    int id;
    char name[20];
} Person;

int main() {
    list_t list = {0};
    type_t person_type;

    // Register the user-defined type
    list_register_user_type(&person_type, sizeof(Person));

    // Create and insert a new Person
    Person p1 = {1, "Alice"};
    list_push_back(&list, &p1, sizeof(Person), person_type);

    Person p2 = {2, "Bob"};
    list_push_front(&list, &p2, sizeof(Person), person_type);

    // Print list size
    printf("List size: %zu\\n", list_size(&list));

    // Print list content
    for (node_t* node = list_begin(&list); node != NULL; node = node->next) {
        if (node->type == person_type) {
            Person *p = (Person*)node->data;
            printf("Person: ID=%d, Name=%s\\n", p->id, p->name);
        }
    }

    // Clean up
    list_clear(&list);
    return 0;
}
.fi

Program output:
.RS
List size: 2
Person: ID=2, Name=Bob
Person: ID=1, Name=Alice
.RE
